Impromptu market and bread shopping @dupainetdesidees - picked up beautiful fresh strawberries, asparagus and tomatoes as well as terrine, rabbit (!) and more! (And if you have Alexa enabled, apologies if my IG Live turned it on. I’ve been resisting using it but thought I’d finally give it a try when I bought a new speaker that included it…and she decided to start playing music during the video, and some commenters said me talking about it turned their “Alexas” on too😅😁) What do you look forward to most at the market in the summer?
.

node.text: Polenta de maïs grand roux basque (red corn Polenta from the Basque region) with chorizo for dinner - I used the Golden Pheasant (an American brand of polenta) technique of cooking it in the oven using 1 part polenta (about a cup…I didn’t have a measuring cup, so I used a big mug😉) to 4 parts (~1l) water, teaspoon salt and a tablespoon olive oil. Bake in a buttered non-stick baking dish (although I think I’ve done it in a regular one but the recipe recommends nonstick and since I was cooking for others I didn’t want to mess it up) in a 350F/180C oven for 40m. Gave a stir, tasted for salt and baked 10m more. If adding sausage like I did, add sliced sausage during the last 10mn of cooking. Voilà…dinner! (I do like stirring some Parmesan into polenta after it’s cooked, which I didn’t do this time, but it makes it even better imho.)

node.text:
When I ordered a glass of Pineau des Charentes at a café in Angoulême I asked for a glaçon (ice cube). The serveuse said “Sacriledge!”….with a  chuckle. While I was told a few weeks ago when in this region, the Charentes, that it was “pas normal.” But when I was at @cognacpasquet there was an ad on the shelf of the tasting room they told me was from the 80s (swipe left/second photo) that suggested filling the glass with ice. So my one cube seems modest by comparison🧊😅!
.
If you drink Pineau des Charentes, are you on team ice…or not?

node.text: Someone made vin de pissenlit, aka: dandelion wine for us to try from what they picked in their backyard…it was good!
